title: Customer service done right!
text: I recently purchased your Premium package, which I am very happy about, (of optimumblinds.net) after a free trial I to learn the product but I had a couple issues. After several calls to try to figure out the issues, and frankly nothing was solved, I called again and on my next call your John Rene received my call. John solved everything!! John was extremely knowledgeable about your product and his service was top-notch and he was excellent (and friendly) to deal with as well! We even shared a few good laughs! I was not happy when I called but I knew almost instantly that John knew your product and I was confident he would be able to resolve the issues, which he did very well! Sadly, in today's culture customer service isn't a very high priority. This why I am so impressed with John Rene so much! John was nothing short of incredible, efficient, and professional which is not the norm in customer service today. I am so appreciative of John's patience and diligence that I feel it necessary to contact Go Daddy to tell you of John Rene's diligence and excellence. I imagine with a high amount of confidence that John consistently serves every customer of your company he deals with in the same prudent and professionally intelligent manner. I personally think this young man deserves a raise and also think John should train other employees (some frankly need a little help in the customer service department). I hope upper management sees this message. I believe someone who is very good at what they do should be acknowledged and rewarded. That’s why I am writing this message. I hope John Rene is rewarded by Go Daddy! John Rene was not only, by far, the most talented and knowledgeable Go Daddy employee I have dealt but also the best customer service representative I have done business with in any company in a very long time. Our phone call was over 2 hours! Thank you to Go Daddy for having such a great employee and for having an awesome website builder. Talent like John Rene is hard to find! By the way, I will be purchasing another Premium package website in the future about my research. I am a very happy customer!! And a lot of that happiness can be attributed to John Rene. I wish you all well.

title: Unsafe, insecure and then suddenly, all together invisible! GoDaddy helped me rectify it all!
text: As a life coach who works with clients online, by phone and in person, my website is essential as my representation to people who are seeking assistance (and particularly those who are not local), as the place where sessions or coaching packages are purchased. Imagine my surprise and horror when a new client informed me that as she tried to pay for a coaching session, a warning message came up saying it was not safe to share personal information on that page! I immediately spent an hour on the phone with the GoDaddy help department, and found out that I had to update my outdated marketing system. I tried to arrange to pay for the update with a credit card that was awaiting its latest payment before it would allow my purchase to go through. The GoDaddy representative there gave me all available discounts and refunds for time I had paid for but would not be able to use with the old system, and then patiently waited over the next few days for my credit card payment to be applied. I immediately began working to replace the one page of my website where online purchases are available but when I went to publish what I thought was a single page of a six page website, that one page replaced my entire website, leaving the payment page and nothing else! The entire original website had vanished into the ether-world! The next two days. I worked with the website maintenance and design team to help me try to restore my original website and just change the payment page to make my website user and payment friendly. After a marathon 3-hour call, we were able to modernize and improve my website, using the old text content while also making it safe and reassuring for clients that want to pay for coaching online. In each department where I received assistance, the GoDaddy staff were knowledgeable, patient, polite and extremely helpful. After just one day down, my website is live again, looking more modern and attractive than it has in years! I look forward to working with them again soon to help me with my SEO!

title: Complete failure as an email service provider on every level
text: I've been on the phone with support no less than 15 times over this and get a different person every time. Immediately after locking me out of my email and requiring me to remove and make changes to my email software account settings to re-access it, two things happened. I lost all my old email prior to that point (last June) and my mailbox has registered as full, or close to it, for the first time ever in my decade-old account with you. Look at the screenshots. I have less than 400 total emails in my inbox. Yet the settings indicate there are almost 3,000 and I can't clear that out. I get a full mailbox alert every week and have to clear out any junk to squeak out a little more space each time. Before you ask, I have escalated the issue several times. I have asked for a manager several times. I have been told ridiculous things each time about the discrepancy between the small amount of emails in my inbox that only date back to June, and the amounts listed in my settings. I am plugged to pay more to upgrade my service each time. I AM  PAYING TOO MUCH RIGHT NOW FOR THE LIMIT OF 500 OR SO EMAILS AT MY AVAILABILITY, FROM A COMPANY THAT LOST THOUSANDS OF MY EMAILS CAUSING IRREPARABLE HARM TO ME. Forgive the all caps but I am exhausted with dealing with this major breakdown in service that has cost me way too many hours of my life. I am not calling the support line anymore. I will continue to post on social media until the matter is resolved on your end and you reach out to me to confirm. Thank you.

title: I renewed my hosting plan on line and…
text: I renewed my hosting plan on line and did so w/o referring to a discount offer I had received for 20% off of the renewal fee. I attempted to see if the discount offer would be applied through the Chat available. It was instantly apparent that would not work for my situation. So I tried the Text option, naively thinking this would be a real person on the other end. I can only assume it wasn't because after 2hr 20min I had received three (3) requests for my PIN and customer number, and told to hold on twice so they might check for the appropriate discount. I had already sent them a screen shot of the offer I was emailed and a screen shot of the product I was trying to renew. After this 2hr + text exchange I attempted to reach someone by phone. After placing the call I was on hold for 12 minutes at which time I was cut off. I tried again and after 9 minutes I was able to speak with someone who ultimately answered my question. It shouldn't be this difficult, nor should it take as long as it did in my case. I realize no one has enough staff and it's hard to find people to work but I think you would be better served to take less inquiries that are resolved w/o leaving the customer hanging for an extended period than trying to respond to every call you get right then.  I also think people would understand this. Surely anyone that's been out to eat would relate to how hard it is to have staff. Instead of repeating " we can't wait to exceed your expectations" every minute or so, be more genuine and let them know you're working through whatever it is and that you are trying to get them taken care of. It's a little disingenuous to go on about how you can't wait to exceed the customer's expectation when you can meet a basic expectation of taking/responding to their question.

title: In a world of Catch 22's, GoDaddy shined
text: Due to Google ending their free G-suite email service, they suspended Mom's email, causing all her emails to get returned to sender as undeliverable. Since it was a free product, Google offered no way to get this resolved. The only way was to access was through Google workspace online, which required using an account with admin privileges. Since I set this up for Mom in 2008, I had no recollection of creating a separate email address for admin purposes. After digging through old emails, a week later Mom found the admin account name. Of course, password unknown, to reset I needed access to Mom's email which was suspended. Fortunately, I had purchased Mom's domain through GoDaddy and not Google, had we had used Google, the domain would have been lost. I had no idea what Mom's GoDaddy account and password were, so we went through the GoDaddy account recovery form, which online stated a response in 3 days, no response, so I called. Speaking to a GoDaddy support member, I was told that the wait time was 7 days not 3. After 7 days I called in again, that GoDaddy support rep checked with account recovery and said, not 3, nor 7, days, but 22 days. 22 days passed I called again, this time I got Michelle, she checked with next tier support, and they told her I was not even in the queue for account recovery. Note the other 3 support reps told me I was definitely in the queue and to be patient. Michelle found this unacceptable and worked with me for over an hour to gain access to my account, she helped by modifying DNS for me to get at TXT record to Google to gain access to my Google workspace account, then a MX record to get my emails sent to another provider while I worked on the google account. It sure would have been to my advantage had the first support rep been Michelle! Thanks Michelle, you worked MAGIC!

title: Thumbs down to GoDaddy
text: Got an email from GoDaddy this morning that my primary email account (that I use for my business) would be suspended in TWO days. Woke me up!!!! Signed on to GoDaddy. Waited in queue for 1hr and 3mins... while the recording "we can't wait to exceed your expectations..." replayed at interminably short intervals. Also, to my recollection that cheesy message about due to unforeseen blah.. blah... has been playing since Covid began. My primary email was due to auto-renew A MONTH LATER. One of my other domain email accts was due to renew 5 DAYS LATER.  Checked my payment methods (I have 2 on file) and all were good. Tried to find out what the renewal costs would be for these products. Couldn't navigate their site. Lots of "Upgrade..", "Get More..", "Extra$..." etc., but no "How Much?". Speaking of which... have you ever noticed how much more expensive Internet Domain related products cost at time of renewal compared to initial setup? Surely, it's much cheaper to renew than the cost to the provider of setting up the service. If I buy a magazine subscription and the publisher offers a reduced cost for a period, seems to me the publisher always lets me know how much to renew? Hmmm? To me, having email service is much akin to having healthcare service. You can't be without it. The one bright thing about my discouraging episode with GoDaddy was my contact with the customer service gentleman. Despite the fact that our call was crackled and we couldn't hear one another for long periods of time he hung in - as did I. His name was Rick. He promised to pass my comments and the recorded conversation up the chain of management - for review. Hopefully, to somebody who gives a damn!

title: GoDaddy's illegal behaviour should be reported to the ACCC
text: GoDaddy should be referred to the ACCC for illegal terms. If you toggle 'autorenew' to 'off' in the Dashboard, the privacy and protection that you currently have on a domain will be removed and you will have to pay $10 to put it back on. This is illegal because you paid for that cover at the same time you paid for the domain and it should not expire until the domain expires.  I have been with GoDaddy for at least 2 years and currently have 6 domains there. Until now I didn't have to use their support team but because of what's happened, and the support response, I will definitely be moving my business elsewhere.  In more detail: Yesterday I turned off autorenewal on 2 domains that are not due to expire for almost 2 and 6 months. I did this via the Domain page on the Dashboard. The same page shows that Privacy is unchanged (still on) but I received an email saying that it had been removed because of my actions. When I called GoDaddy about it, I was told that yes, it was removed because I had removed autorenewal on those domains. When questioned the grounds of this, I was told that it was my fault that I hadn't phoned Support to make the changes (instead of doing it via Dashboard). (And note that I'd already been on hold to Support for over half an hour.) I was also told that the Dashboard was only for turning on autorenewal, not off. Then the phone went silent and eventually he hung up on me.  The next day I called again and got a nicer person. Unfortunately, she told me the same thing: that yes, privacy and protection were removed because I had removed autorenewal and I would have to pay $10 to put each one back on. When I questioned the details re legality of this, she was about to read to me what the exact words had been in the confirmation text that I'd agreed to (and I said I would write it down) but then, suddenly, the line went silent and then cut off - once again.  Clearly very dodgy and I can assure GoDaddy that after this experience, they have lost a customer with multiple domains. I actually think this behaviour is illegal and should come to the attention of the ACCC. I paid for domain privacy and protection for 12 months. There is nothing on the Dashboard saying that if I toggle autorenew off (for the next year), that I forfeit any remaining protection on my existing domains (especially without refund). And how dodgy is it that your tech support have no sensible answers in this situation and can only cut the line off when the questions get too hard? I hope I can upload some screenshots here from my GoDaddy Dashboard and the email I received.
